title: For Sale:  Once fired Berdan primed 7.62X51 brass
postcontent:
Just sorted through my brass and I have a good bit of once fired berdan primed 7.62X51 brass.  Various head stamps, some South African, Portuguese, Argentine, Czech, maybe more.  Don't know how many without counting by hand but I'd say it's easily over 1K since I've shot probably 2500 rounds total through my rifle (I'm keeping the boxer primed stuff).  I have it in a 12.7qt container and it's almost full so that gives you an idea of how much brass we're looking at.  

FYI - please know the difference between BERDAN and BOXER primers.  If you are looking to reload, this is probably NOT for you.  There are instructions on the web about converting berdan brass to accept boxer primers but it is labor intensive and can be dangerous so do at your own risk. For Sale:  12ga Tristar Brittany
postcontent: Brittany Model 12ga Chambered for 3". This gun was imported by Tristar and was made by Zabala Hermanos of Spain. This gun was made in 2005 and the condition is excellent plus, this gun is On Face and tight with the opening lever to the right of center. There are a couple of scratches on the rich polished blued barrels and also a couple very minor dings in the stock. This gun has a Single Selective trigger, English straight stock and semi-beavertail forend, Ejectors (which are strong and timed) and a nice engraved Case Colored action. The guns 26 3/4" barrels also comes with 5 choke tubes, two tubes are original to the gun (Modified and Full) and three are tubes from Carlson Choke Tubes (Skeet, Improved Cylinder and Improved Modified). All tubes except for the Full and IM are rated for steel shot. The wood grain is better than most Brittany's and the color of the wood is darker than what the pictures show. This gun is a lightweight at 6lbs 9oz. Most Brittany's run in the 7lb plus range. This would make a nice all day carry for the uplands. The specs for this gun are: LOP, 14 1/8" to the end of the buttplate, DAC is 1 1/2" and DAH is 2 1/4". The gun is Cast Off about an 1/8". title: For Sale:  M95 Nagant Revolver with .32ACP Conversion Cylinder
postcontent:
For sale today is a beautiful 1895 Nagant Revolver made at Tula Arsenal, Russia in 1937. I've had a number of these over the years and this one is the best  example. The bluing is rich, dark and is 99.9% intact with no imperfections that I can see. The revolver also has a bright bore with no  pitting or rust, and all the others that I've owned had dark, butserviceable bores. Additionally the grips are a deep dark walnut color while all the others I've owned always had light wood (almost blond) colored grips. Bottom line is that you'd be hard pressed to try to upgrade this revolver. 

It comes with an original and well marked holster that is in absolutely excellent condition along with an original cord type lanyard. There is also an original  wood handle Nagant screwdriver & cleaning rod both of which stow away in the holster. 

Perhaps the most interesting feature is the new & never fired conversion cylinder chambered for .32 ACP which is much less expensive and easier to find than  the original cartridge - the 7.62 Nagant. These conversion cylinders were available for a time about 10 years ago, but have become next to impossible to  find today. The conversion cylinders do require some hand fitting since the factory tolerances on the M95 varied slightly  over time. I have done the fitting so now all that is required is some normal use.  

Finally one 50 round box of PPU brass case/non corrosive 7.62 Nagant ammo is included as well as one 50 round box of Fiocchi .32 ACP 

Price is $350 with pickup in the Valrico/Brandon area. You must be a Florida resident and at least 21 years old to purchase. Thanks for looking.
